1 Load and process data

data <- read_csv('data/all_cleaned_scored.csv') %>% 
  mutate(sex = factor(sex))

# Create dataframe just with the subset of participants interested in weight loss.
data_iiwl <- data[data$IWL == 'yes',]

# create sample size strings of "N=XXX" to use as information on the plots
n_all <- sprintf("N=%d", length(na.omit(data$logk_money)))
n_iiwl <- sprintf("N=%d", length(na.omit(data$logk_weight)))

# frequency of sex in the data
sex_freq <- count(data, sex)
n_female <- sex_freq$n[sex_freq$sex=='female']
n_male <- sex_freq$n[sex_freq$sex=='male']

When we closed the survey we had a total of 408 respondents. Because this was an unsupervised online questionnaire we took efforts to ensure the data quality was high. While the respondents were all unpaid volunteers, and therefore had some level of intrinsic motivation to complete the questionnaire accurately, we used fairly strict exclusion criteria. We first removed 22 participants on the basis of missing or incorrect responses, or who were under 18. We excluded one participant who did not disclose their sex assigned at birth. In the scoring procedure we calculated the number of responses correctly predicted by the hyperbolic discount function and corresponding discount tates. We removed participants where we were unable to predict 70% of more of their responses. This lead to 1 participant being exluded on the basis of the MCQ and 3 on the basis of the WCQ. We decided not to exclude participants who always chose the delayed reward. This is most likely due to the limited range of discount rates that the MCQ is sensitive to rather than aberrant responding.

After participant exclusion we have N=381 participants in total (242 female and 139 male). Of these, N=257 reported being interested in weight loss. Because all participants completed the MCQ, we calculated the \(\log(k)\) for discounting of money for all N=381 participants. Only participants interested in weight loss completed the MCQ, so we were able to calculate the \(\log(k)\) for discounting of weight loss for N=257 participants. Note that all log discount rates correspond to the natural logarithm.

2.3 Discounting for money versus weight loss

Figure 2.2 shows the joint distribution of discount rates for money and weight loss. A Bayesian 1-tailed test for a positive correlation between discount rate types shows decisive evidence for a positive correlation (\(BF_{+0}=27,628\)). However the effect size is small, with only around 9% of shared variance, \(R^2\) = 0.091 (95% CI: 0.034, 0.166) (see discounting money vs weight.jasp).

lnk_by_type <- ggplot(data_iiwl, aes(x=logk_money, y=logk_weight, color=sex)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, aes(fill=sex)) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) + 
  coord_fixed(ratio = 1) +
  labs(x="ln(k) money", y="ln(k) weight loss", subtitle = n_iiwl) +
  apatheme +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.85, 0.2))

lnk_by_type

Figure 2.2: Joint distribution between discount rates for money and weight loss. People falling along the diagonal discount money and weight loss at the same amount. We cannot say anything about the exchange rate between weight loss and money because we did not do a cross-commodity discounting test. 

ggsave(file.path("figs/lnk_by_type.pdf"), 
       plot = lnk_by_type)
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

There was no evidence of a different relationship for males and females. We ran a Bayesian ANCOVA to predict logk_money, with sex as a fixed factor and logk_weight as a predictor. We also explored if there was an interaction between sex and discounting for weight loss, and so the full model considered was logk_money ~ logk_weight + sex + logk_weight * sex. The best account of the data was given by logk_money ~ logk_weight. Adding in a main effect of sex is 4 times worse than the best model, counting as substantial evidence against a main effect of sex. The evidence against the remaining models is even stronger.

Overall we can decisively conclude that the different discount rates are correlated, but that they only share approximately 9% of the variance. We can also decisively conclude that there is no main or interaction effect with sex, and so the relationship between the different discount rates is identical for both men and women.

Table 1: Bayesian ANCOVA model and submodels to predict logk_weight. We report Bayes Factors (BF01) relative to the best model (model 1, logk_money ~ logk_weight). Model 1 corresponds to model stated in each row. Therefore BF10 values greater than 1 show evidence against a given model relative to the the best model. See the supplementary file discounting money vs weight.jasp.

2.3.1 Predictors of money/weight loss discounting ratio?

However, it is interesting that there are people who discount money at a faster rate than weight loss and people who discount weight loss at a faster rate than money. This raises the interesting question of whether there is a relationship between the ratio of discount rates and BMI or age. Visually, there is no compelling relationship between either age or BMI and the ratio of the discount rates (see Figure 2.3).

We ran a Bayesian ANCOVA with the discount rate ratio as the outcome variable. We included sex as a fixed factor, and age and bmi as covariates, and considered interactions between sex and bmi and age. The best model to explain the data was the null model, indicating that neither sex nor age nor bmi could predict the ratio of discount rates. The next best model was a main effect of bmi, however this was slightly worse than the null model at accounting for the data (BF=3.39). All other models were even worse, and so we have convincing evidence that sex, age, bmi or various interactions are not related to the ration between discount rates for weight loss and money.

2.5 BMI by age and sex

It is known from larger scale surveys (Sutin and Ferrucci 2011) that there is a dependence of BMI upon age. This relationship is nonlinear over the entire lifespan, with decreases seen in adolescence following a rise in adult life, with a later decrease beyond the age of around 60. We decided to model the BMI and age relationship as a linear trend based on: a) this being true to a first approximation for our age range of 18-80, b) not having sufficient data at the older age range to accurately estimate a non-linear relationship. Figure 2.5 shows clear increases in BMI as a function of age.

A Bayesian ANCOVA was run to examine bmi ~ age + sex + sex*age and all sub-models. The best model is bmi ~ age which had decisive evidence for the main effect of age, as compared to a null model (BF=2.395 * 1017 ). 3 Does discounting predict BMI?

One of the core research questions in this study was whether discount rates (for money or for weight loss) could predict BMI. We first present the straightforward correlations between discounting and BMI. We then present the results of an analysis which adjusts for the effects of age and sex. While the first approach is required in order to compare our results to correlations presented in the literature, we argue that the latter approach should be used more. Age and sex clearly influence discounting, and so any claim that discounting influences BMI, should really take both age and sex into account.

3.1 Correlations between discounting and BMI

Many previous studies report correlation coefficients between discount rates and BMI. This is an entirely reasonable analysis to run, but in the next section we argue that future studies need to go further than this. But here we simply ask, what is the correlation between discounting and BMI. Figure 3.1 explores this visually.

money_bmi <- ggplot(data, aes(logk_money, bmi)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.2) +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', colour='black') +
  apatheme +
  labs(y=expression(paste("BMI [", kg/m^2, "]")), 
       x="ln(k) money",
       subtitle=n_all)

weight_bmi <- ggplot(data_iiwl, aes(logk_weight, bmi)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.2) +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', colour='black') +
  apatheme +
  labs(y=expression(paste("BMI [", kg/m^2, "]")), 
       x="ln(k) weight loss",
       subtitle=n_iiwl)

bmi_discounting <- ggarrange(money_bmi, weight_bmi, ncol=2, nrow=1)

Figure 3.1: Lack of relation between bmi and discounting. This lack of relationship holds for discounting of money (left column) and of weight loss (right column).

       plot = bmi_discounting)
## Saving 7 x 4 in image

A Bayesian regression bmi ~ logk_money + logk_weight + logk_money * logk_weight showed that there were no main effects nor an interaction of discount rates. That is, a null intercept only model was the best model. There was significant evidence against the next best model (a main effect of logk_money). In other words, we find significant evidence against either discount rate playing a role in BMI.

Table 6: Does discounting predict bmi? We present Bayes Factors as BF01 relative to the null model (model 0), such that values of BF01 greater than one represent evidence against a given model relative to the null model. See does discounting predict bmi.jasp.

We ran a Bayesian correlation to test the hypothesis that there is a correlation between discount rates for money and BMI (see does discounting predict bmi.jasp). We found substantial evidence against the hypothesis BF01=7.997, meaning the data is about 8 times more probable under the null hypothesis. The median Pearson correlation coefficient was R=0.059 [95% CI: -0.041, 0.158].

We ran a Bayesian correlation to test the hypothesis that there is a correlation between discount rates for weight loss and BMI (see does discounting predict bmi.jasp). We found strong evidence against the hypothesis BF01=12.391, meaning the data is about 12 times more probable under the null hypothesis. The median Pearson correlation coefficient was R=0.016 [95% CI: -0.106, 0.137].

3.2 Adjusting for age

We argue that if the goal is to assess the role of discounting in BMI, then it is critical to account for age. Failing to do this could mean that studies with different participant age distributions would come to different conclusions. As we know from previous work, BMI varies as a function of age (Sutin and Ferrucci 2011). Figure 2.5 clearly shows this in our dataset.

What does accounting for age actually mean? If we were to find a main effect of discounting even after removing variance accounted for by age, then this would be evidence that discount rates were predictive of BMI. In other words, it would mean that BMI increases with age, but for a given age those who discount at a higher rate would have a higher BMI.

We ran a Bayesian ANOVA, the outcome variable was bmi. Covariates were age, logk_money and logk_weight. The best model was bmi ~ age. The fact that all other models have \(BF_{10}<1\) (i.e. \(BF_{01}>1\)) means that adding additional main effects (logk_money and/or logk_weight) make the data less likely relative to the bmi ~ age model. We have anecdotal evidence against a main effect of logk_money or logk_weight, and moderate evidence against both main effects of logk_money and logk_weight.

Table 7: Does discounting predict BMI when accounting for age? No. The data is most likely under a main effect of age. Note that we present Bayes Factors relative to the best model (bmi ~ age) and so the fact that BF01 are all >1 means that there is evendence against these models relative to the best model. For example the data becomes \(\sim 5.3\) times less likely when adding a main effect of logk_money. See does discounting predict bmi.jasp.

We did not include the interaction terms logk_money * age or logk_weight * age as this would amount to a moderation analysis. We reserve this for evaluation of our ‘rate of gain’ hypothesis - this was undertaken (in Python code). Those results are reported in the main paper as well as the corresponding Python code in the online Supplementary Material.

In summary, and in reference to Table 7, our core findings were:

  1. BMI is best accounted for by a main effect of age. This data is about \(2.395 \times 10^{17}\) more likely than the null model, so this is decisive evidence for the bmi ~ age model.

  2. We have evidence against main effects of either logk_money or logk_weight.

3.3 Summary

In our first analysis which did not take age or sex into account, we found moderate evidence against main effects of either discount rate on BMI, and strong evidence against an interaction of discount rate types on BMI. This, together with the correlation coefficients and corresponding Bayes Factors suggest discount rates alone are not predictive of BMI. Further, in our last analysis which did take age and sex into account, we found very strong evidence that age linearly predicts BMI, and that models incorporating main effects of either discount rate were worse than this BMI ~ age model. This provides evidence against the hypothesis that discounting processes might drive behaviours which in turn cause a rate of BMI increase over the lifespan.

4 Analysis of Stunkard ratings

As well as the objective BMI measure, we also measured the participants subjective belief about their body size via the Stunkard Figure Rating Scale (Stunkard, Sørensen, and Schulsinger 1983).

4.1 BMI and Stunkard ratings

Figure 4.1 shows the relationship between BMI and Stunkard score. The Stunkard score is bounded between 1-9, and the Stunkard score saturates in a non-linear manner at very high BMI levels. That is, we seem to have a slight ceiling effect which is causing this subtle non-linear relationship. We fitted this with the function \(stunkard = 9 \cdot (1-\exp(-(BMI+BMI_0)/\tau))\), where \(\tau\) controls the steepness of the function and \(BMI_0\) shifts the function along the x-axis.

ggplot(data, aes(x=bmi, y=stunkard)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.7)+
  geom_smooth(method='lm', color='black') +
  geom_smooth(method = "nls", 
              formula = y ~ ifelse(x>x0, 9*(1-exp(-(x+x0)/tau)), 1),
              method.args = list(start=c(tau=50, x0=18)),
              se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE, color='black') +
  #scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,65)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(1,9), breaks=c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9)) +
  apatheme +
  labs(x=expression(paste("BMI [", kg/m^2, "]")), 
       y="Stunkard rating", 
       subtitle = n_all)

Figure 4.1: The relationship between BMI and Stunkard score. We show both a linear and a nonlinear fit (see text).

A visual inspection (see Figure 4.2) does not reveal any compelling linear relationships. We conducted Bayesian ANCOVA with stunkard as our outcome variable, sex as a fixed factor, and logk_money and logk_weight as covariates. The null model was the best model, suggesting none of our variables could predict the SFRS score. There is however some scope for a relationshion here, which might be elucidated in future studies. The Bayes Factors for the next best model only provide anecdotal evidence against a role for sex and discount rates and possibly an interaction between sex and discount rates.

Table 8: Any predictors of Stunkard scores? We present Bayes Factors BF01 relative to the best (which is also the null model, model 0) such that values of BF01 greater than 1 represent evidence against a given model. See stunkard.jasp.

Based upon the descriptive statistics reported above, broken down by sex, we see that the average Stunkard score is marginally higher for women (4.7) than men (4.5).
